{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-03-17T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"St Patrick, the patron saint of Ireland, was born in Roman Britain around the late 4th or early 5th century. According to legend, at 16, he was kidnapped by Irish raiders and brought to Ireland as a slave. After escaping, he returned home and later became a missionary, spreading Christianity across the island. He is famously associated, according to later tradition, with using the shamrock to explain the Holy Trinity. His legacy of faith has made St Patrick's Day a global celebration.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DonegalFort_EN-GB9523764542_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DonegalFort_EN-GB9523764542_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Ireland's spiritual crossroads","Title":"Grianan of Aileach ring fort, Donegal, Ireland","Copyright":"© aluxum/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/55.023849,-7.427537/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=55.023849,-7.427537;S9;Grianan of Aileach, Donegal, Ireland&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260317_DonegalFort\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Saint+Patricks+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260317_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260317_DonegalFort"},"Ssd":"20260317","Name":"DonegalFort","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"9523764542","FullDateString":"17 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"With their black-and-white coats and gentle demeanour, pandas have become global symbols of conservation. Observed on 16 March, National Panda Day highlights this iconic species and the conservation challenges it still faces. Giant pandas are native to China and have faced a high risk of extinction due to habitat loss and low birth rates. Thanks to global conservation efforts, their population is slowly recovering, but more work is needed.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PandaForest_EN-GB2508441209_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PandaForest_EN-GB2508441209_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Into the Pandaverse","Title":"Giant panda eating bamboo, China","Copyright":"© Entwicklungsknecht/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Despite being carnivores, giant pandas eat mostly bamboo and spend hours daily consuming it to make up for its low nutrition.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260316_PandaForest\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=giant+panda&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260316_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260316_PandaForest"},"Ssd":"20260316","Name":"PandaForest","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"2508441209","FullDateString":"16 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Before the kettle boils on Mothering Sunday, a robin is already at work. Spring is its busiest season, and parenting is in full swing. This bird may look small, but it runs a tight family operation. The female selects the nest site and builds a cup of moss and leaves. She incubates the eggs, staying put while life develops beneath her. Meanwhile, the male plays provider, delivering insects to keep her fuelled. Once the chicks hatch, both parents feed them every few minutes. No snooze button, no packed lunches—just beaks full of worms.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.MotheringSunday2026_EN-GB9211202468_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.MotheringSunday2026_EN-GB9211202468_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A peck of care","Title":"A robin feeding its chick, Netherlands","Copyright":"© CreativeNature_nl/iStock/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Robins use a technique where they rub ants or millipedes on their feathers to act as a natural insecticide.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260315_MotheringSunday2026\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Mothering+Sunday+March&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260315_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260315_MotheringSunday2026"},"Ssd":"20260315","Name":"MotheringSunday2026","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"9211202468","FullDateString":"15 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Long before pi had a name, people were drawn to its mystery. Every year on March 14, Pi Day highlights one of math's most recognisable constants. The date reflects the first three digits of pi (π), the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter: 3.14. Pi's infinite, nonrepeating decimal has fascinated thinkers for a long time. The modern celebration began in 1988, when physicist Larry Shaw marked the day with a fitting tribute: serving pie.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CornwallDolmen_EN-GB7624290325_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CornwallDolmen_EN-GB7624290325_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"An ancient angle on Pi","Title":"Lanyon Quoit, a Neolithic dolmen in Cornwall, England","Copyright":"© Helen Hotson/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/50.147726,-5.599093/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=50.147726,-5.599093;S9;Lanyon Quoit, Cornwall, England&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260314_CornwallDolmen\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Pi+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260314_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260314_CornwallDolmen"},"Ssd":"20260314","Name":"CornwallDolmen","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"7624290325","FullDateString":"14 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Under the vaulted ceiling of Notre-Dame de Bon-Port in Les Sables-d'Olonne, a seaside town in western France, the stone ribs still guide the gaze upward. Construction of the soaring vaults began in 1646. The church—officially recognised as a French historic monument since 1993—stands on the site of a 13th-century chapel, a reminder of deep-rooted spiritual life on the Atlantic coast.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.VendeeVaults_EN-GB7453353937_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.VendeeVaults_EN-GB7453353937_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A quiet masterpiece in stone","Title":"Vaults of the Church of Notre Dame de Bon-Port, Les Sables-d'Olonne, France","Copyright":"© Helmut Meyer zur Capellen/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/46.496203,-1.786035/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=46.496203,-1.786035;S9;Notre Dame de Bon-Port, Les Sables-d'Olonne, France&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260313_VendeeVaults\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Notre+Dame+de+Bon+Port+Les-Sables+France&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260313_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260313_VendeeVaults"},"Ssd":"20260313","Name":"VendeeVaults","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"7453353937","FullDateString":"13 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"High in Ecuador's cloud forests, a young sunbittern spreads its wings in an early display, casting flashes of orange, black and white through the filtered green light. The sudden contrast cuts through the moss‑covered branches and leaf‑shadowed understorey, offering a snapshot of the species' dramatic wing patterns. Adult sunbitterns most often show these bold markings during defensive displays, briefly transforming an elusive bird into a striking spectacle.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SunbitternEcuador_EN-GB7250985153_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SunbitternEcuador_EN-GB7250985153_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Wings in rehearsal","Title":"Juvenile sunbittern displaying at nest, Ecuador","Copyright":"© Andy Rouse/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The sunbittern's wings feature eye‑like patterns, often revealed during wing displays in low forest light.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260312_SunbitternEcuador\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=sunbittern+bird&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260312_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260312_SunbitternEcuador"},"Ssd":"20260312","Name":"SunbitternEcuador","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"7250985153","FullDateString":"12 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Spring hits differently in Cieza. It doesn't gently unfold—it erupts with colour. Between February and March, this small city in Spain's Murcia region is the epicentre of 'La Floración,' the flowering of peach trees. In a matter of days, more than 12,000 acres (5,000 hectares)—Spain's largest municipal peach production—transform into the sea of colour we see in today's image.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PeachBloom_EN-GB7084568493_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PeachBloom_EN-GB7084568493_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"A peachy keen spring","Title":"Peach trees in bloom, Cieza, Murcia, Spain","Copyright":"© Juan Maria Coy Vergara/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/38.239372,-1.418669/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=38.239372,-1.418669;S9;Cieza, Murcia, Spain&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260311_PeachBloom\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Cieza+Spain&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260311_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260311_PeachBloom"},"Ssd":"20260311","Name":"PeachBloom","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"7084568493","FullDateString":"11 Mar 2026"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"From above, East Lake Cherry Blossom Park in Wuhan, China, looks like a soft lilac cloud settled gently over the land. Thousands of cherry trees bloom at once, their pale petals forming a living canopy around a golden five-storey pagoda at the park's heart. The pagoda rises in calm symmetry, its tiered rooflines glowing against the delicate pastels of spring.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.WuhanCherryBlossom_EN-GB4535197537_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.WuhanCherryBlossom_EN-GB4535197537_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":false},"Headline":"The shape of spring","Title":"Cherry blossoms at East Lake Cherry Blossom Park, Wuhan, China","Copyright":"© Zhang Qiao/VCG/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/30.595,114.2975/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=30.595,114.2975;S9;Wuhan, Hubei, China&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260324_WuhanCherryBlossom\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Wuhan+China&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260324_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260324_WuhanCherryBlossom"},"Ssd":"20260324","Name":"WuhanCherryBlossom","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"4535197537","FullDateString":"24 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The strength of nature is nowhere more evident than in powerful storms. Scary? Yes. Fascinating? Even more so. Learning to understand and respect these forces helps humanity live more safely.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SonoranStorm_EN-GB4374217480_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SonoranStorm_EN-GB4374217480_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Guided by the weather","Title":"Lightning storm over saguaro cacti, Sonoran Desert, Arizona, United States","Copyright":"© Jack Dykinga/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/32.248009,-112.91613/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=32.248009,-112.91613;S9;Sonoran Desert, Arizona, United States&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260323_SonoranStorm\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Meteorological+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260323_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260323_SonoranStorm"},"Ssd":"20260323","Name":"SonoranStorm","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"4374217480","FullDateString":"23 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today is World Water Day, declared by the UN in 1992 and first observed the following year. Humanity could no longer drift along—we had to safeguard the very currents that keep us alive. Few places capture that urgency like Lake Tanganyika, in the Great Rift Valley of eastern Africa. From space, it's a roughly 420‑mile ribbon linking Tanzania, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Zambia. At the shoreline, it's a 10-million-year-old rift basin, formed as the Earth's crust slowly pulled apart.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TanganyikaWater_EN-GB4227251929_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TanganyikaWater_EN-GB4227251929_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"When water draws the line","Title":"Lake Tanganyika, Africa","Copyright":"© BEST-BACKGROUNDS/NASA/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/-6.026425,29.475387/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=-6.026425,29.475387;S9;Lake Tanganyika, Africa&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260322_TanganyikaWater\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=World+Water+Day&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260322_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260322_TanganyikaWater"},"Ssd":"20260322","Name":"TanganyikaWater","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"4227251929","FullDateString":"22 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If Earth had a maintenance crew, forests would be spearheading it. They absorb carbon emissions, reduce soil erosion, safeguard biodiversity, influence rainfall and help maintain clean water supplies. They still cover about 31% of the world's land area, yet their continued decline shows how vulnerable these natural systems have become. Vast stretches continue to be cleared for agriculture, infrastructure and resource extraction, weakening ecosystems at an alarming rate.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LeteaForest_EN-GB4037759034_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LeteaForest_EN-GB4037759034_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Where roots run wild","Title":"Letea Forest, Danube Delta, Romania","Copyright":"© Wild Wonders of Europe/Widstrand/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"The UN FAO estimates that about 24.7 million acres (10 million hectares) of forest are cut down each year.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260321_LeteaForest\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=International+Day+of+Forests&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260321_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260321_LeteaForest"},"Ssd":"20260321","Name":"LeteaForest","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"4037759034","FullDateString":"21 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A white snowdrop is spring's quiet debut. No confetti, no countdown—just a delicate flower appearing as the spring equinox balances day and night. Snowdrops are among the first to bloom, often pushing through cold soil before winter fully packs up. Their drooping, bell-shaped flowers may look delicate, but they're built for early arrival. Special antifreeze proteins in their cells help them tolerate frost, making them well suited to unpredictable late-winter weather.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpringSnowdrops_EN-GB6031515717_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpringSnowdrops_EN-GB6031515717_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"The quiet bloom of change","Title":"Snowdrops in spring","Copyright":"© klagyivik/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"Collectors crazy about snowdrops are called galanthophiles.","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260320_SpringSnowdrops\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=March+equinox&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260320_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260320_SpringSnowdrops"},"Ssd":"20260320","Name":"SpringSnowdrops","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"6031515717","FullDateString":"20 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"An egg-laying mammal. No teeth. Reptilian gait. Built-in body armour. If the short-beaked echidna sounds like a checklist of contradictions, that's because it is—and it owns it. Native to Australia, Tasmania and parts of New Guinea, it's one of the few surviving monotremes, or mammals that lay eggs. Despite the headlines, it still qualifies as a mammal: it has fur, produces milk and is warm-blooded. The twist? Milk is released through specialised skin patches rather than nipples, leaving the young to lap it up.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.EchidnaAustralia_EN-GB9662090948_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.EchidnaAustralia_EN-GB9662090948_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Spike your curiosity","Title":"Short-beaked echidna, Adelaide Hills, Australia","Copyright":"© Etienne Littlefair/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/-34.892811,138.836243/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=-34.892811,138.836243;S9;Adelaide Hills, South Australia&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260319_EchidnaAustralia\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Short-beaked+echidna&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260319_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260319_EchidnaAustralia"},"Ssd":"20260319","Name":"EchidnaAustralia","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"9662090948","FullDateString":"19 Mar 2026"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Spring break on Vancouver Island looks a little different. In Canada, the Pacific Rim Whale Festival celebrates the annual spring migration of thousands of grey whales as they pass close to the island's west coast. Created by local communities in the 1980s, the festival marks the whales' return north from breeding lagoons in Baja California, Mexico.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PacificRimNP_EN-GB7806112812_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PacificRimNP_EN-GB7806112812_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Passing through, making waves","Title":"Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, Vancouver Island, Canada","Copyright":"© EmilyNorton/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"//platform.bing.com/geo/REST/v1/Imagery/Map/RoadVibrant/49.068329,-125.753273/4?key=AsSOKo7OOz5VAtfAj0rjgaXlhCrCZI6PGbLj7GCH8IW2HUalyg4BVhqA0z77PRCj&c=en-GB&od=2&shading=flat&pp=49.068329,-125.753273;S9;Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, Vancouver Island, Canada&st=pp|v:false;lv:false_trs|v:false;lv:false&ml=Basemap,Landmarks&logo=no&mapSize=386,434&da=ro","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260318_PacificRimNP\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Pacific+Rim+Whale+Festival&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260318_0000\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260318_PacificRimNP"},"Ssd":"20260318","Name":"PacificRimNP","Market":"EN-GB","Hash":"7806112812","FullDateString":"18 Mar 2026"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Image of the day","LOC_H